{"title_page": "Arnold K. Garr", "text_new": "{{BLP primary sources|date=November 2018}}\n'''Arnold Kent Garr'''<ref>Middle name from [[United States Copyright Office]] entry.  See {{cite web | title=A History of \"Liahona the Elders' journal\" : a magazine published for ... /... | work=Copyright Catalog (1978 to present) | publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]] | url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=4&ti=1,4&Search_Arg=garr%20arnold&Search_Code=NALL&CNT=25&PID=p5I3Bjv0VH7D16K4TFk3lGh486a&SEQ=20090713172154&SID=1 | accessdate=2009-07-13}}</ref> (born June 14, 1944) was the chair of the department of Church History and Doctrine at [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) from 2006 to 2009.  He was also the lead editor of the ''Encyclopedia of Latter-day Saint History''.\n\n== Biography ==\nGarr was born and raised in [[Ogden, Utah]].  As a young man, Garr served a [[Missionary (LDS Church)|mission]] for [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) in [[Finland]].  Garr married Cherie Burns in the [[Salt Lake Temple]] on November 20, 1967 and they are the parents of five children.<ref name=BYUmag>{{cite journal | title=Following Beacons of Light | author=Zawrotny, B. Robert | journal=BYU Magazine | date=Summer 2004 | url=http://magazine.byu.edu/?act=view&a=1507 | accessdate=2009-07-13}}</ref><ref name=millennial>{{cite book | author=Garr, Arnold K. | title=Joseph Smith: Presidential Candidate | chapter=Author's Biographical Information | series=Setting the Record Straight | publisher=Millennial Press | location=Orem, Utah | isbn=978-1-932597-53-0 | year=2007 | page=125}}</ref>\n\nIn the LDS Church, among other callings, Garr has served as a [[Bishop (LDS Church)|bishop]], counselor to a [[stake president]], member of a [[stake high council]] and [[branch president]].  He served as a member of the [[Church Correlation Committee]] from 2001 to 2009.\n\nLate in his life Garr took up running and he completed eleven [[marathons]] after turning sixty.<ref name=millennial/>\n\n===Education===\nGarr received a [[bachelor's degree]] in History from [[Weber State University]], a [[master's degree]] in History from [[Utah State University]], and a Ph.D. in American History, minoring in LDS Church history, from BYU in 1986.<ref name=BYUmag/><ref name=millennial/>\n\n===Career===\nGarr began his career with the [[Church Educational System]] (CES) as a [[LDS Seminary|seminary]] teacher at [[Roy, Utah|Roy]] High School in [[Utah]].  He later served as director of the [[Institutes of Religion]] in [[Rochester, New York]], [[Boulder, Colorado]] and [[Tallahassee, Florida]].  After 21 years with CES, Garr joined the BYU faculty in 1991.<ref>[http://reled.byu.edu/vitas/faculty/Arnold%20Garr%20Vita.pdf Garr's vita] {{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref><ref name=millennial/>  He taught at the [[BYU Jerusalem Center]] during 1996\u201397 and was later the chair of the Department of Church History and Doctrine.<ref name=millennial/>\n\n==Publications==\n*{{Cite thesis\n | author    = Garr, Arnold K.\n | title     = A History of Brigham Young College, Logan, Utah\n | year      = 1973\n | degree    = Master's\n | publisher = Department of History, [[Utah State University]]\n}}.\n*{{Cite thesis\n | author    = Garr, Arnold K.\n | title     = A History of Liahona the Elder's Journal: A Magazine Published For the Mormon Missions of America, 1903-1945\n | year      = 1986\n | degree    = Doctoral\n | publisher = Department of History, [[Brigham Young University]]\n}}.\n*{{cite book\n | author    = Garr, Arnold K.\n | title     = Christopher Columbus: A Latter-day Saint Perspective\n | year      = 1992\n | publisher = [[Religious Studies Center]], [[Brigham Young University]]\n | location  = Provo, Utah\n | isbn      = 0-88494-842-0\n | url       = http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/u?/rsc,18724\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | editor1-last  = Garr, Arnold K.\n | editor2-last  = Johnson\n | editor2-first = Clark V.\n | title         = Missouri\n | series        = Regional Studies in Latter-day Saint Church History\n | year          = 1994\n | publisher     = Department of Church History and Doctrine, [[Brigham Young University]]\n | location      = Provo, Utah\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author    = Garr, Arnold K.\n | chapter   = Theodore Roosevelt and the Latter-day Saints\n | title     = Out of Obscurity: The LDS Church in the Twentieth Century\n | series    = 29th Annual Sidney B. Sperry Symposium\n | year      = 2000\n | publisher = [[Deseret Book]]\n | location  = Provo, Utah\n | isbn      = 1-57345-842-2\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | editor1-last  = Garr, Arnold K.\n | editor1-first = \n | editor2-last  = Cannon\n | editor2-first = Donald Q.\n | editor2-link  = Donald Q. Cannon\n | editor3-last  = Cowan\n | editor3-first = Richard O.\n | editor3-link  = Richard O. Cowan\n | title         = Encyclopedia of Latter-Day Saint History\n | year          = 2000\n | publisher     = [[Deseret Book]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City, Utah\n | isbn          = 1-57345-822-8\n | oclc          = 44634356\n | others        = Holzapfel, Richard Neitzel (photographic editor) \n}}\n*{{cite journal\n | author    = Garr, Arnold K.\n | title     = Bishop Daniel S. Tuttle: Episcopalian Pioneer Among the Mormons\n | journal   = [[Mormon Historical Studies]]\n | volume    = 1\n | issue     = 2\n | date      = Fall 2000\n | pages     = 78\u201380\n | url       = http://www.mormonhistoricsitesfoundation.org/publications/studies_fall2000/mhs1.2GarrFall2000.pdf\n}}\n*{{cite journal\n | author    = Garr, Arnold K.\n | title     = Which Are the Most Important Mormon Books?\n | journal   = [[BYU Studies]]\n | volume    = 41\n | issue     = 3\n | date      = 2002\n | pages     = 35\u201347\n | url       = http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/u?/byustudies,4284\n}}\n*{{cite book\n |editor1-last=Cannon \n |editor1-first=Donald Q. \n |editor1-link=Donald Q. Cannon \n |editor2-last=Garr \n |editor2-first=Arnold K. \n |editor3-last=Van Orden \n |editor3-first=Bruce A. \n |title=The New England States \n |series=Regional Studies in Latter-day Saint Church History \n |volume=5 \n |year=2004 \n |publisher=[[Religious Studies Center]], [[Brigham Young University]] \n |location=Provo, Utah \n |isbn=0-8425-2583-1 \n |url=http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/u?/rsc,20380 \n |url-status=dead \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612034159/http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/u/?%2Frsc%2C20380 \n |archive-date=2011-06-12 \n |df= \n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author    = Kettley, Marlene C. |author2=Arnold K. Garr |author3-link=Craig K. Manscill |author3=Craig K. Manscill\n | title     = Mormon Thoroughfare: A History of the Church in Illinois, 1830-1839\n | year      = 2006\n | publisher = [[Religious Studies Center]], [[Brigham Young University]]\n | location  = Provo, Utah\n | isbn      = 0-8425-2652-8\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author    = Garr, Arnold K.\n | title     = Joseph Smith: Presidential Candidate\n | series    = Setting the Record Straight\n | year      = 2007\n | publisher = Millennial Press\n | location  = Orem, Utah\n | isbn      = 978-1-932597-53-0\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100611172312/http://religion.byu.edu/sing_fac.php?f=Arnold%20K.&l=Garr BYU faculty bio]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite magazine |url= https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1996/10/growing-with-a-living-church?lang=eng |first= Arnold K. |last= Garr |title= Growing with a Living Church |magazine= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= October 1996 |page= 25}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://religion.byu.edu/arnold_garr BYU Religious Education Faculty website]\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-2972221}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garr, Arnold K.}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:American Latter Day Saint writers]]\n[[Category:American Mormon missionaries in Finland]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Cat